<p>San Diego residents can take advantage of multiple incentive programs to reduce the cost of solar and HVAC installations. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% credit on the total cost of solar panel systems installed through 2032, then steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the full system cost including equipment, installation, and permitting fees, making it one of the most valuable solar incentives available.</p>

<p>At the state level, California's Self-Generation Incentive Program (SGIP) offers rebates for battery storage systems that pair with solar installations. While SDG&E discontinued most solar rebates due to high adoption rates, they continue to offer rebates for energy-efficient HVAC systems through their Energy Efficiency programs. The utility provides rebates ranging from \$75 to \$400 for qualifying high-efficiency air conditioners, heat pumps, and smart thermostats. Additionally, San Diego County and many municipalities offer expedited permitting and reduced fees for solar installations, helping to lower soft costs and installation timelines.</p>

